We are building and pushing the main Image for Jenkins container on an EC2 instance because i dont want to install docker locally. (Disk Space Issue) 

STEP 1 — Spin Up a Temporary Build EC2

Use Terraform (or console if you want speed for now)

Minimum spec:
Instance: t3.medium (or t3.large if faster builds needed)

Storage: 30–50GB (important)

OS: Amazon Linux 2 or Ubuntu

🔐 Attach IAM Role (IMPORTANT)

Attach policy:

AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryFullAccess

👉 This avoids login headaches later.

🚀 STEP 2 — SSH into Instance
ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>
🚀 STEP 3 — Install Docker on the Instance

For Amazon Linux:

sudo yum update -y
sudo amazon-linux-extras install docker -y
sudo service docker start
sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

Then:

exit

SSH back in (so group applies)

🔍 Verify
docker --version
docker run hello-world
🚀 STEP 4 — Copy Your Dockerfile to EC2

From your local machine the directory(folder where you have the docker file for your jenkins image) ( mine is in project-commands folder):

scp -i your-key.pem Dockerfile ec2-user@<public-ip>:/home/ec2-user/

mine :   scp -i ~/Downloads/us-east-1-key.pem dockerfile ec2-user@<public-ip>:/home/ec2-user/
dockerfile 

If you have more files you want to move into your Jenkins EC2 run this:

scp -i your-key.pem -r . ec2-user@<public-ip>:/home/ec2-user/


🚀 STEP 5 — Build Image on EC2

docker build -t jenkins-custom .

🚀 STEP 6 — Create Repo in Amazon ECR or if you already have ECR repo, skip this step, just log into it and push

aws ecr create-repository \
  --repository-name jenkins \
  --region us-east-1

  OR configure your AWS user on the instance 

 
🚀 STEP 7 — Login to ECR
aws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-1 \
| docker login \
--username AWS \
--password-stdin <account-id>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com


The <account-id> should be your account id


🚀 STEP 8 — Tag Image

(  Note : You can tag your Image as v1 or  v2 or v3 etc. depending on the version of your app  but ensure it is consistent and that is what you call in your setup.sh script if you tag it v1 call v1 in your script if you tage it v2 call v2 in your script)

docker tag jenkins-custom:latest \
<account-id>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/jenkins:vi


docker tag jenkins-custom:latest \
761018849945.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/jenkins:v1

🚀 STEP 9 — Push Image
docker push <account-id>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/jenkins:v1


docker push 761018849945.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/jenkins:v1



💣 STEP 10 — Destroy the Build Instance

👉 This is the part most people don’t do — and waste money.

After push is complete:

exit

Then:

Terminate EC2

✔ Image is safe in ECR
✔ No more compute cost

Immediate Action You SHOULD take

Add lifecycle policy (VERY important in Prod):

Keep only last 2–3 images.

